Below is from the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Jerome Biblical Commentary</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> on Daniel. <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>24</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>seventy weeks</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Or 'seventy Sabbatical periods.' The change from the 70 years of Jeremiah to 7 times 70 years is based not only on the fact that Israel's lack of complete repentance merited this sevenfold punishment (Lv 26:18), but also on 2 Chr 36:21, where Jeremiah's prophecy is connected with the Sabbatical years spoken of in Lv 26:34-35. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>24</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> A brief summary of the whole period of the 490 years.  If reckoned at its longest from the time that Jeremiah first spoke his prophecy (605) to the end of Antiochus IV Epiphanes' persecution (164), this period would only be 441 years.  But the writer, who no doubt knew little of the chronology of the early post-exilic period, would not be disturbed by this discrepancy between his symbolic numbers and the historical facts.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>a most holy will be anointed</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->:  Almost certainly refers to the consecration by Judas Maccabeus of the restored Holy of Holies in the Jerusalem Temple, but the Church Fathers often applied it to Jesus, 'the Anointed One.'<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>25-27.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The three main periods of the 490 years.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>25.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>one who is anointed a leader:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Probably Cyrus the Great (cf. Is 45:1); less likely Zerubbabel or the high priest Joshua.  Only if one reckons from the second utterance of Jeremiah's prophecy (<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>ca.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 595) to the anointing of Cyrus as king of Persia (558--a date the writer of Dn 9 would hardly know!) could be the required 49 years be approximately obtained.  But the following words imply that the first period extends to the beginning of the rebuilding of Jerusalem, which would embrace much more than seven weeks of years.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>sixty-two weeks:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> The 62 weeks of years, or 434 years, allowed for the rebuilding of Jerusalem are too many by far; from 538 to 171 (the next date) is only 367 years.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>26.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>an anointed shall be cut down:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> The reference is certainly to the murder of the deposed high priest, Onias III, in 171, in Antioch; hence 'when he does not possess the city of Jerusalem' (cf. 2 Mc 4:5,33-36).  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the people of a leader:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  The Syrian army of Antiochus IV Epiphanes, which plundered the Jerusalem Temple in 169 and 167.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>27.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>for one week:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> If counted from the murder of Onias in 171, this period would last from 170-163.  The writer's hopes that the persecution would not last beyond 163 were fully realized.  He probably wrote a few months before the persecution ended in December of 164. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> a firm pack with many:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> An alliance made by Antiochus IV Epiphanes with the renegade Jews who favored the Hellenization of their culture (cf. 1 Mc 1:11-14).  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>half the week:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> The second half of the seven year period beginning in 170. ( On the symbolic value of three and one-half years, see comment on 7:25.) The desecration of the Temple actually lasted only three years--from December, 167, to December, 164 (1 Mc 1:54; 4:52).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
